Text: Depo is a type of birth control that you get every 3 months to prevent pregnancy. Lots of girls just call it “the shot” and it works by preventing ovulation (when your body releases an egg) - no egg, no baby! If you don’t mind getting it every 3 months, you should definitely talk to your doctor about getting started.

Text: The shot has a few potential side effects. You’ve probably heard that a big one is weight gain - which is true. But, it’s the only birth control that might make you gain a few extra pounds. Other side effects are spotting between periods and a change in appetite.

Text: The implant is a type of birth control that goes into your upper arm to prevent pregnancy. It used to be called Implanon but now it’s called Nexplanon. It’s a teeny rod that releases progestin to stop ovulation (no egg, no baby) and thickens mucus in your cervix.
